ce:section.ce:para:
The sensory results reflect the microbial and chemical alterations that occur in meat with and without C-dots. As shown in Fig. 8
                        , the synthesized C-dots had minimal impact on meat color but improved odor scores in sensory panel evaluations during refrigerated storage of the treated samples. Sensory color analysis was in agreement with the results obtained from color analysis by colorimeter (Table 2
                        ). The spraying of CDs resulted in a reduction in L*, a* and b* values of the meat. The decrease in L* in the treated samples is evident because the color of C-dots influences the lightness of the meat surface. Furthermore, due to the prevention of off-odor in the treated groups compared to the control group, the treatment group received better overall acceptability scores from sensory panelists. Notably, this distinct odor, characterized by smoky notes, was attributed to C-dots. However, in terms of color, the C-dot-treated meat imparted a darker color to the treated group. Wen et al. (2023) investigated the effects of turmeric-derived synthesized C-dots in a chitosan matrix for preparing a series of active composite films for pork packaging. Sensory evaluation revealed that C-dots effectively prevented off-odor and meat discoloration. The differences in color and odor observed in the present study compared to other studies could be attributed to variations in the methods of applying the antimicrobial agent to the food item or the intrinsic properties of the C-dots themselves, such as color and viscosity.
